      {
        "accepted_answer": false,
        "actions_summary": [],
        "admin": false,
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/forum.bambulab.com/professional3d/{size}/106684_2.png",
        "badges_granted": [],
        "bookmarked": false,
        "can_accept_answer": false,
        "can_delete": false,
        "can_edit": false,
        "can_recover": false,
        "can_see_hidden_post": false,
        "can_unaccept_answer": false,
        "can_view_edit_history": true,
        "can_wiki": false,
        "cooked": "<aside class=\"quote no-group\" data-username=\"jrwagz\" data-post=\"8\" data-topic=\"211145\">\n<div class=\"title\">\n<div class=\"quote-controls\"></div>\n<img alt=\"\" width=\"24\" height=\"24\" src=\"https://forum.bambulab.com/user_avatar/forum.bambulab.com/jrwagz/48/131741_2.png\" class=\"avatar\"> jrwagz:</div>\n<blockquote>\n<p>global $fn</p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>In my approach, resolution represents the physical length of each polygon segment, analogous to the XY resolution of a 3D printer. Why drive a crazy $fn if the user cannot see it and the printer cannot print it?</p>\n<p>A global fn forces the same high segment count onto every circle, cylinder sphere, linear_extrude, rotate_extrude and offset, regardless of size.<br>\ncircle(d=1, $fn=200) costs essentially the same as circle(d=2000, $fn=200), even though the small one gains nothing visually.</p>\n<p>Deriving $fn from a target resolution keeps segment length roughly constant, so small features use few segments and large ones only get more where needed.<br>\nThat cuts polygon count early, before CSG evaluation, which is where OpenSCAD actually gets slow.<br>\nNothing becomes magically smoother, you are just expressing smoothness in physical units instead of an arbitrary global number.</p>",
